description: iOS rule for Swift and SwiftUI app code: view composition, state ownership, @MainActor, structured concurrency, cancellation, and actor isolation.
globs: ["**/ios/**/*.swift", "**/*.xcodeproj/**", "**/*.xcworkspace/**", "**/Package.swift"]
alwaysApply: false
---

# ios swiftui

- Prefer native SwiftUI building blocks and platform-consistent interaction patterns before introducing custom UI systems.
- Keep views composable and focused. Move orchestration, networking, persistence, and nontrivial transformation logic out of view bodies.
- Use explicit state ownership. Keep long-lived observable state in dedicated models or view models and keep views as clear render surfaces.
- Mark UI-bound state and mutations with `@MainActor` where appropriate. Do not casually update UI-observed state from background execution contexts.
- Treat Swift concurrency as a design constraint: prefer structured concurrency, preserve cancellation, and avoid detached work unless it is clearly justified.
- Be deliberate about task lifetime. Tie asynchronous work to view or feature lifetime and cancel work that is no longer relevant.
- Keep actor and isolation boundaries understandable. Do not silence concurrency warnings by weakening isolation without explaining the tradeoff.
- Prefer small reusable views, clear navigation structure, accessibility-aware controls, and platform-consistent interaction feedback.
- Keep project structure legible across app entry, shared UI, models, services, utilities, and tests, but adapt to the repository that already exists.
